WEDNESDAY, May 2.

The Speaker took the chair about eleven o'clock.

THIRD READINGS.

The following bills were read a third time and passed, to amend the Ordi­nance respecting mortgages and sales of personal property ; to, incorporate Edmonton Public Hospital; respecting clerks and deputy clerks ; respectin sheriffs and deputy sheriffs; to amen the Pound Ordinance; to grant further powers to the town of Lethbridge; to âmend the Ordinance adding a certain area to the municipality of Indian Head : to amend the Agricultural Societies Ordinance; to amend and consolidate the Brand Ordinance.

TEIE VILLAGE ORDINANCE.

When the Village Ordinance bill came up for third reading,

Mr. Ij. H. McDonald moved that it be referred back to committee for the purpose of being amended to the effect that a village could not be erected if a. majority of the people protested. , He

the Ordinance had all along been ob­jected to by members of the opposi­tion. The amendment was lost and the bill read a third time. BULLS, ETC., Mr. Bulyea moved the second read; ing of a bill respecting stallions and buils. The object was to provide that the close season for bulls running at large should be curtailed. Heretofore buils had been allowed to run at large between July 1st and March 31st. The bill provided that this period should be reduced and that liberty only allowed between July 1st and December 31st. The bill was read a second time. THE LIQUOR LAW. Últimately the bill passed through committee without alterations. THE SCHOOL ORDINANCE. Mr. Haultain moved second reading of a bill to amend the School Ordi­nance. He said that in a future more or less remote he hoped there would be a general auditor-for the whole of the school accounts of the Territories. They were not, however, ready for that to-day; but the bill proposed to apply the principle to some groups of districts where the persons could not read or write in English. Another point the bill dealt with was the child­ren of non-resident ratepayers. Non­resident ratepayers had the right, to send their children to schools; and a man might buy a small $5 lot, and so get the privilege of sending his child­ren in the town schools. The bill pro­vided that non-resident ratepayers should not have the privilege when their assessment was. less than the average assessment of the ratepayers in the town. The bill was read a second time. T.AX S.A.L.E. Mr. Haultain moved second reading of a bill respecting confirmation of sales of land for taxes. He said the object of the bill was that the produc­tion by proper officers of evidence of sale would be taken by the judge as proper evidence of the validity of the tax. The bill covered both municipal and school taxes.—Carried.

PATRIOTIC GRANTS.

Mr. Hauitain moved second reading of a bill to legalise the payment of grants by municipalties for patriotic purposes. He said there were sºme doubts as to whether municipalties were strictly within their rights in the grants recently made for patriotic pur­poses, and he therefore ºpº the passage of this enabling bill,—Carried.

REGINA HOSPITAL.

Mr. G. W. Brown proposed second reading of a bill to incorporate Regina hospital. The bill would enable G.T. Marsh, A. McDonald, F. N. Darke, Jas. Balfour, I). J. Goggin; G. Michea­lis, W. G. Pettingell, G. H. V. Rulyea, G. W. Brown and such other persons as from time to time might become members of the corporation, to be in­corporated a body politic under the maine of the Reginal Hospital. The corporation would be enabled to ac­quire real and personal estate, pro­vided the real estate did not exceed $40,000. The bill contained the usual provisions as to management. A onation of $50 entitles the doner to life membership, and the annual sub­scribers will have a right to take part in the annual meeting. Provision is also made for the free vaccination of all poor persons, and of any others at a charge of not more than 75 cents. The bill was read a second time. The House then went into committee of the whole, when several bills were advanced a stage. In the dentistry bill the qualification for students, in regard to the second class non-profes­º certificate was left as in the old 111. The House adjourned at half past noſ).m.
